  "notes": "Old English / Anglo-Saxon (~450–1150 CE). West Saxon literary standard; 4 dialects: West Saxon, Northumbrian, Mercian, Kentish. KEY FEATURES: Breaking (ea, eo diphthongs before -rC, -lC, -h); i-umlaut (mann/menn); Ingvaeonic nasal spirant law (mūþ, fīf, ūs); Palatalisation: *k→[tʃ] / ⟨c⟩ before front V (cild 'child'); *g→[j] before front V (gear 'year'); ⟨sc⟩ = /ʃ/ (scip 'ship'); ⟨cg⟩ = /dʒ/ (ecg 'edge'); ⟨f⟩ = [v] between voiced sounds. Primary texts: Beowulf, Anglo-Saxon Chronicle, Ælfric's Homilies. Source: Campbell (1959), Hogg (1992).",
